  "prompt": "Is it too late to start a computer science degree if I am 20 and don't know any programming languages?",
  "response": "It's definitely not too late to start a computer science degree at 20, even if you don't know any programming languages yet! Many students begin their studies in computer science without prior programming experience. College programs are designed to teach you the fundamentals and gradually build your knowledge and skills over time.\n\nHere are a few reasons why it's not too late:\n\n1. **Structured Learning**: Computer science programs typically start with introductory courses that teach the basics of programming and computational thinking.\n\n2. **Resources**: There are many resources available, such as textbooks, online courses, tutorials, and coding boot camps, that can help you learn at your own pace.\n\n3. **Support**: Universities often provide support through tutoring centers, study groups, and office hours with professors to help you succeed.\n\n4. **Industry Growth**: The tech industry is growing rapidly, and there is a high demand for skilled professionals. Starting your degree at 20 gives you plenty of time to gain experience and enter the workforce.\n\n5. **Age Factor**: It\u2019s common for people to start their degrees at various ages. Being 20 means you have several years ahead to learn, intern, and build your career.\n\nIf you're passionate about computer science and willing to put in the effort, you can definitely succeed in this field. Consider exploring introductory programming resources to get a head start and see if this is a path you want to pursue. Good luck!",
